@article{10.1145/3360564,
    abstract = {Byzantine fault-tolerant state-machine replication 
(BFT-SMR) is a technique for hardening systems to tolerate arbitrary 
faults. Although robust, BFT-SMR protocols are very costly in terms of 
the number of required replicas (3f+1 to tolerate f faults) and of 
exchanged messages. However, with "hybrid" architectures, where 
"normal" components trust some "special" components to provide 
properties in a trustworthy manner, the cost of using BFT can be 
dramatically reduced. Unfortunately, even though such hybridization 
techniques decrease the message/time/space complexity of BFT 
protocols, they also increase their structural complexity.  Therefore, 
we introduce Asphalion, the first theorem prover-based framework for 
verifying implementations of hybrid systems and protocols. It relies 
