have significantly different perceptions of the game(s) they are 
playing. Past work with hypergames has focused on relatively simple 
interactions consisting of a small set of discrete choices for each 
player. Here, we apply single-stage hypergames to larger systems with 
continuous variables. We find that manipulating constraints can be a 
