spintronic devices due to its unique properties: small area, no 
spin-charge signal conversion, zero leakage current, non-volatile 
memory, high density, low operating voltage, and its compatibility 
with conventional CMOS technology. In this article, we extend the work 
in Reference [1] on the usage of ASLD to produce secure and resilient 
circuits that withstand IC attacks (during the fabrication) and PA 
attacks (after fabrication), including reverse engineering attacks. 
First, we show that ASLD has another unique feature: identical power 
dissipation through the switching operations, where such properties 
