@article{10.1145/3185593,
    abstract = {Online harassment is a complex and growing problem. On 
Twitter, one mechanism people use to avoid harassment is the 
blocklist, a list of accounts that are preemptively blocked from 
interacting with a subscriber. In this article, we present a rich 
description of Twitter blocklists -- why they are needed, how they 
work, and their strengths and weaknesses in practice. Next, we use 
blocklists to interrogate online harassment -- the forms it takes, as 
well as tactics used by harassers. Specifically, we interviewed both 
people who use blocklists to protect themselves, and people who are 
blocked by blocklists. We find that users are not adequately protected 
from harassment, and at the same time, many people feel that they are 
blocked unnecessarily and unfairly. Moreover, we find that not all 
users agree on what constitutes harassment. Based on our findings, we 
propose design interventions for social network sites with the aim of 
